#function to get train and test files for a folder path
def getFileNames(path):
    files = []
    for (dirp, dirn, filen) in walk(path):
        files.extend(filen)
        break
    print(files)
    labelsTrain = []
    labelsTest = []
    fileNameTrain = []
    fileNameTest = []
    for f in files:
        if f.startswith('train'):
            labelsTrain.append(int(f.replace('train','').replace('.csv','')))
            fileNameTrain.append(f)
        elif f.startswith('test'):
            labelsTest.append(int(f.replace('test','').replace('.csv','')))
            fileNameTest.append(f)


    summaryFileDf_train= pd.DataFrame({'fileName': fileNameTrain ,'labelsTrain': labelsTrain})
    summaryFileDf_test= pd.DataFrame({'fileName': fileNameTest ,'labelsTest': labelsTest})
    return summaryFileDf_train,summaryFileDf_test
In [202]:
#function to read the csv files in a folder path where there are multiple train test files
def readFiles(path,header):
    FileDf_train,FileDf_test = getFileNames(path)
    print(FileDf_train.head())
    print(FileDf_test.head())
    traindataset = pd.DataFrame()
    testdataset = pd.DataFrame()
    for f in FileDf_train.iterrows():
        tempdf = {}
        file = path + f[1]['fileName']
        if(header == False): 
            tempdf = pd.read_csv(file,skiprows=[0],header=None)
        else:
            tempdf = pd.read_csv(file)
            print(1)
        if len(FileDf_train) > 1: 
            print('multi' + str(f[1]['labelsTrain']))
            tempdf['Label'] = f[1]['labelsTrain']
            traindataset =  pd.concat([traindataset,tempdf]) 
        else:
            traindataset = tempdf
    for f in FileDf_test.iterrows():
        tempdftest = {}
        file = path + f[1]['fileName']
        #print(file)
        if(header == False): 
            tempdftest = pd.read_csv(file,skiprows=[0],header=None)
            #print(2)
        else:
            tempdftest = pd.read_csv(file)
            #print(1)
        if len(FileDf_test) > 1: 
            #print('multi')
            tempdftest['Label'] = f[1]['labelsTest']
            testdataset = pd.concat([testdataset,tempdftest]) 
        else:
            testdataset = tempdftest
        
    return traindataset,testdataset

In [212]:
def parameterstoUse(col,val,df,totalColSum):
    partition = df[df[col]==val]
    sizeofPartition = partition.shape[0]
    classpPart = partition[partition['V1']=='p'].shape[0]
    classePart = partition[partition['V1']=='e'].shape[0]
    maxClass = max(classpPart,classePart)
    #print(str(classpPart) + "********" + str(classePart))
    #print("maxClass" + str(maxClass))
    #print("sizeofPartition" + str(sizeofPartition))
    prob = round(sizeofPartition/totalColSum,4)
    return classpPart,classePart,maxClass,sizeofPartition,prob

def calculateAccuracy(col,val,df,totalColSum):
    classpPart,classePart,maxClass,sizeofPartition,prob= parameterstoUse(col,val,df,totalColSum)
    accuracy = round(maxClass/sizeofPartition,4)
    return accuracy,prob


def calculateGINIIndex(col,val,df,totalColSum):
    classpPart,classePart,maxClass,sizeofPartition,prob= parameterstoUse(col,val,df,totalColSum)
    classpProb = classpPart/sizeofPartition
    classeProb = classePart/sizeofPartition
    giniIndex = round((classpProb * classpProb) + (classeProb*classeProb),4)
    return giniIndex,prob 

def calculateEntropy(col,val,df,totalColSum,baseval):
    classpPart,classePart,maxClass,sizeofPartition,prob= parameterstoUse(col,val,df,totalColSum)
    classpProb = classpPart/sizeofPartition
    classeProb = classePart/sizeofPartition
    #print(str(classpProb) + "____" + str(classeProb))
    e1p = 0 
    e1e = 0
    if classpProb > 0:
        e1p = -classpProb*math.log(classpProb,baseval) 
    if  classeProb > 0:
        e1e = -classeProb*math.log(classeProb,baseval)
        #print(e1e)
    entropy =  round(e1p+e1e,4)  
    return entropy,prob
In [213]:
columnList = list(mushroom_train.iloc[:,2:])
part = {}
resultFeat = []
resultAcc = []
resultGini = []
resultEntropy = []

for col in columnList:
    if col!='V17':
        totalAccuracy = 0
        totalginiIndex = 0
        totalEntropy = 0
        accuracy = 0
        part= mushroom_train[col].unique() 
        #print("len" + str(len(part)))
        totalColSum = mushroom_train[col].shape[0]
        for val in part:
            #mushroom_train[i==val].shape[0] 
            #print(col)
            #print(val)
            accuracy,prob = calculateAccuracy(col,val,mushroom_train,totalColSum)
            #print("Accuracy" + str(accuracy))
            #print(prob)
            totalAccuracy = round(totalAccuracy + prob * accuracy,4)
            gini,prob = calculateGINIIndex(col,val,mushroom_train,totalColSum)
            totalginiIndex = round(totalginiIndex + prob * gini,4)
            baseval = len(part)
            #print("baseval" + str(baseval))
            entropy,prob = calculateEntropy(col,val,mushroom_train,totalColSum,baseval)
            totalEntropy = round(totalEntropy + prob * entropy,4)
        #print("Total Acc"  + str(totalAccuracy))
        #print("Total gini"  + str(totalginiIndex))
       # print("Total entropy"  + str(totalEntropy))
        resultFeat.append(col)
        resultAcc.append(totalAccuracy)
        resultGini.append(totalginiIndex)
        resultEntropy.append(1-totalEntropy)
summaryDf= pd.DataFrame({'Feature_name': resultFeat ,'Accuracy': resultAcc ,'GINI Index': resultGini ,'1-Entropy': resultEntropy })

Summary Q2 :¶

  • Created three methods as above to calculate Accuracy , GINI Index and 1-Entropy using the formulae explained in class
  • Further also applied normalization by taking region probability across the feature to balance the dataset region counts for that feature
  • Below is the summary of values

In [218]:
def encodeDataset(dataset):
    for col in dataset.columns:
        if dataset[col].dtype == type(object):
            labEncoder = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
            dataset[col] = labEncoder.fit_transform(dataset[col])
    return dataset

Y_train = mushroom_train.iloc[:, 1:2].values.ravel()

In [224]:
from sklearn.datasets import load_iris
from sklearn.model_selection import cross_val_score
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

 
lambdaArray = []
size_Array = []

dec_score = []
dec_score_train = []
naive_score = []
naive_score_train = []

for lambdaVal in range(0,51,1):
    score = 0
    train_score=0
    lambdaArray.append(lambdaVal)
    naive = GaussianNB(var_smoothing = lambdaVal)
    naivemodel = naive.fit(X_train, Y_train)
    Y_pred = naivemodel.predict(X_test)
    train_score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_train, naivemodel.predict(X_train)),4)
    score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred),4)
    naive_score.append(score)
    naive_score_train.append(train_score)


for size_thresh in range(4,65,4):
    score = 0 
    train_score=0
    size_Array.append(size_thresh)
    decision_model = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=0,min_samples_split=size_thresh)
    model = decision_model.fit(X_train,Y_train)
    Y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    train_score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_train, decision_model.predict(X_train)),4)
    score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(Y_test, Y_pred),4)
    dec_score.append(score)
    dec_score_train.append(train_score)
    
dfNaive = pd.DataFrame({'lambda': lambdaArray , 'AccScore' : naive_score ,'Category' : 'Test' })
df_Naive_train = pd.DataFrame({'lambda': lambdaArray , 'AccScore' : naive_score_train ,'Category' : 'Train'})
dfNaive = pd.concat([dfNaive,df_Naive_train])

dfDec_Tree = pd.DataFrame({'size_thresh': size_Array , 'AccScore' : dec_score,'Category' : 'Test'}) 
dfDec_Tree_train = pd.DataFrame({'size_thresh': size_Array , 'AccScore' : dec_score_train,'Category' : 'Train'}) 
dfDec_Tree = pd.concat([dfDec_Tree,dfDec_Tree_train])

Summary : Looking at the above two plots we can see :¶

  • The test and the train accuracies for both the models go hand in hand for initial part of it
  • Naive Bayes Model : Accuracy starts to drop after lambda of 1
  • Decision Tree Model : The test accuracy starts to drop after threshold of 24
  • Hence the best value of lambda = 2 and best value of sizeThreshhold = 24
  • For NaiveBayes Classifier : the train and test accuracies at lambda = 1 are Train : 0.8308 Test : 0.8111 respectively
  • For Decision Tree : the train and test accuracies at the sizeThreshhold = 24 are : Train : 0.9992 Test : 0.9975 respectively
  • Comparing the two accuracies at the chosen lambda and sizeThreshold we can see that Decision Tree Classifier is performing better than the Naive Bayes

Summary :¶

  • We use standard scalar to standardize the dataset before doing PCA and LDA
  • We further use the PCA and LDA datasets produced to input to the Naive Bayes and Bayes Classifiers
  • Naive Bayes cares\needs only the diagonal variances and hence creates it when the dataset is passed to the Classifier. This is due to its assumptions of independence of features

  • On the other hand Bayes Classifer creates a full covariance matrix when the dataset is passed to it

  • Looking at the above test accuracy for all the four models , we can see that the test accuracy is highest on the fourth model which is on LDA dataset with full covariance matrix. The accuracy there is 0.88833 which is highest amonst the four.

  • The reason for this is two fold :
    • Since in MNIST data there seems to be a dependence between the features , here in this context it implies that the adjacent pixels might be correlated , hence having a dependence and hence a covariance > 0 between dimensions which is clearly used in the Bayesian Classifier. Since this is captured a better and model is produced , moreover in this case LDA is giving a better result than PCA as it captured all the information with n-components = 9 differentiating the features correctly .
    • On contrast if we see once we have done LDA and then doing a Naive Bayes , even that gives a better accuracy than other two on PCA dataset

Q5 : knn and Parzen on MNIST¶

In [677]:
def buildParzenClassifierModel(sigma,classVal,X_train,Y_train):
    X_train_Copy = X_train.copy()
    X_train_Copy["Label"] = Y_train
    X_train_subset = X_train_Copy[X_train_Copy.Label == classVal]
    parzenmodel = KernelDensity(bandwidth=sigma).fit(X_train_subset)
    logprior = np.log(X_train_subset.shape[0] / X_train.shape[0]) 
    return parzenmodel,logprior,X_train_Copy

def buildEntireModel(sigma,X_train,Y_train):
    models =[]  
    logpriors =[]
    priormodel = ''
    for classVal in np.sort(np.unique(all_Y_train)):
        parzenmodel,logprior,X_train_Copy = buildParzenClassifierModel(sigma,classVal,X_train,Y_train)
        logpriors.append(logprior)
        models.append(parzenmodel)
    return models,logpriors 

def predict(X,Y,distinctClasses):
    X_train_pred = X.copy()
    X_train_pred["Label"] = Y
    probabs = np.vstack([model.score_samples(X_train_pred) for model in models]).T
    expprobabs = np.exp(probabs + logpriors)
    pred_prob = expprobabs / expprobabs.sum(1, keepdims=True)   
    return distinctClasses[np.argmax(pred_prob, 1)]

kArray = []
sigma_Array = []

knn_score = []
knn_score_train = []
parzen_score = []
parzen_score_train = []

for k in range(1,19,2):
    print(k)
    score = 0 
    train_score = 0 
    kArray.append(k)
    knn = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    knnmodel = knn.fit(D1_dataset_train, all_Y_train)
    Y_pred = knnmodel.predict(D1_dataset_test)
    train_score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(all_Y_train, knnmodel.predict(D1_dataset_train)),4)
    score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(all_Y_test, Y_pred),4)
    knn_score_train.append(train_score)
    knn_score.append(score)
    
    
distinctClasses= np.sort(np.unique(all_Y_train))
for sigma in np.arange(0.1,3.1,0.1):
    print(sigma)
    score = 0 
    train_score = 0  
    models =[]  
    logpriors =[]
    models,logpriors= buildEntireModel(sigma,D1_dataset_train,all_Y_train)   
    sigma_Array.append(sigma)
    train_score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(all_Y_train, predict(D1_dataset_train,all_Y_train,distinctClasses)),4)
    score = round(metrics.accuracy_score(all_Y_test, predict(D1_dataset_test,all_Y_test,distinctClasses)),4)
    parzen_score.append(score)
    parzen_score_train.append(train_score)

Summary Q5:¶

  • We use knn for KNN Classification

  • For parzen window :

    • Here we build the parzen model with Kernel density function of skikit. We further have to predict the class
    • labels so that we can measure accuracy , for which we use the score samples method that gives us the probabiliy
    • this probability then can be used in conjuction with the priors to further get to a class label using the naive assumptions

  • On D1 :

    • KNN : The optimal K here is: 3. The accuracies there are: At 3 0.879100 Test At 3 0.933300 Train
    • Parzen : The optimal sigma here is: 1.0. The accuracies there are At 1.000000 0.999900 Train At 1.000000 0.961200 Test
  • On D2
    • KNN : The optimal K here is: 3 after which the test accuracy is constant and increases a bit however then the train model accuracy stops dropping. The accuracies there are. Here the test train accuracies have too much diff , which means this is not a good model At 3 0.904400 Test At 3 0.948000 Train
    • Parzen : The optimal sigma here is: 0.3. The accuracies there are At 0.300000 0.985200 Test At 0.300000 1.000000 Train
  • Both Summary :
    • Looking at all the above models we can say that KNN didnt perform as good on D1 as there is a gap in their test and train accuracies. the best model is with Parzen with D2 : Parzen with LDA which gives good Test Train accuracy with a complexity at sigma = 0.3 which is lesser than other Parzen D1

# this method provide the indexes to be used to seperates the dataset that needs to be passed to LDA and not
# this checks for the columns having sum of variance across the classes as zero to remove them before LDA so that we could
#avoid errors or hinderance of those pixels while modelling
def getZeroNonZeroVarianceIndexes(dataset,label1,label2):
    #print(dataset.columns)
    dataset = dataset.iloc[:,1:786]
    #print(dataset.columns)
    newdf = dataset[dataset['Label']==label1].var(axis=0) 
    newdf1 = dataset[dataset['Label']==label2].var(axis=0) 
    newdf3 = newdf + newdf1
    return list(newdf3[newdf3==0].index),list(newdf3[newdf3!=0].index)

# this method divides the master dataset to a subset corresponding to labels provided
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import Normalizer
def defineSubsetsforLDA(label1,label2,isDimsRemoved=False,listNonZero=[]):
    
    listNonZero.append("Label")
    
    if(isDimsRemoved):
        datasetTrain = mnist_dataset_train.loc[:,listNonZero]
        datasetTest =  mnist_dataset_test.loc[:,listNonZero]
    else:
        datasetTrain = mnist_dataset_train
        datasetTest = mnist_dataset_test
    
    X_train = datasetTrain[datasetTrain['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, 1:785].values
    #sc = Normalizer()
    #X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
    Y_train = datasetTrain[datasetTrain['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:,-1].values.ravel()
    print(Y_train)
    X_test = datasetTest[datasetTest['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, 1:785].values
    #X_test = sc.fit_transform(X_test)
    Y_test = datasetTest[datasetTest['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, -1].values.ravel()
  
    return X_train,Y_train,X_test,Y_test

from matplotlib import pyplot as plt # referred DLIOT class tutorial material here 
import numpy as np
def createImage(imageArray):
    two_d = (np.reshape(imageArray, (28, 28)) * 255).astype(np.uint8)
    plt.imshow(two_d)
    return plt
In [313]:
def performLDA(comps,X_train,Y_train,X_test,Y_test): # this method gives the scalings vector which is 
    lda = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(n_components = comps)
    dataset_array_train = lda.fit(X_train, Y_train).scalings_
    dataset_array_test = lda.fit(X_test, Y_test).scalings_
    return dataset_array_train,dataset_array_test

import itertools
imgArray =[]
oldColSeq = list(mnist_dataset_train.iloc[1:2,1:786].columns.values)
if 'Label' in oldColSeq: oldColSeq.remove('Label')
    
my_list = numpy.unique(mnist_dataset_train.Label)
print(my_list)
for pair in itertools.combinations(my_list, r=2):
    print(*pair)
    print("Image plot post LDA Between digits : " + str(pair[0]) + " and " + str(pair[1]))
    lstZero,lstNonZero = getZeroNonZeroVarianceIndexes(mnist_dataset_train,pair[0],pair[1])
    X_train_img,Y_train_img,X_test_img,Y_test_img = defineSubsetsforLDA(pair[0],pair[1],True,lstNonZero)
    print(X_train_img.shape)
    dataset_array_train_img,dataset_array_test_img = performLDA(1,X_train_img,Y_train_img,X_test_img,Y_test_img)
    
    if 'Label' in lstZero: lstZero.remove('Label')
    if 'Label' in lstNonZero: lstNonZero.remove('Label')

   
    zeroListData = numpy.zeros(shape=(1,len(lstZero))) 
    df = pd.DataFrame(zeroListData,columns=lstZero)
   
    imageDF = pd.DataFrame(dataset_array_train_img.transpose(),columns=lstNonZero)
    imageDF = pd.concat([imageDF,df],axis=1)
    imageDF = imageDF[oldColSeq]
    createImage(imageDF.values).show()

  • Looking at the pixels we can see :
    • For digit 1 when compared with all others , the center pixel is higlighted,
      • That center pixel further gets elongated for digits 6 , 5 , 4 and 3
    • Similarly for digit 6 with all other pairs we can see that the top portion of the pixels that make a zero are not highlighted
    • Same way for digit 2 the left bottom pixels dont highlight rest do
    • For pair 6 and 2 , both of them are missing.
    • For pair 3 and 6 the bottom pixels show overlap with differnt color (greenish )
    • For pair 4 and 7 we can see that there is a pixel that has greenish color on the top right , this is the place of overlap too.
      • These pattern follows for the rest of the digits too and hence we can infer that where there is an overlap there might be a possibility of lower prediction power of the model as it cannot differentiate them

In [379]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.preprocessing import Normalizer
def defineSubsets(label1,label2):
    X_train = mnist_dataset_train[mnist_dataset_train['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, 1:785].values
    sc = Normalizer()
    X_train = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
    Y_train = mnist_dataset_train[mnist_dataset_train['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:,-1].values.ravel()
    print(Y_train)
    X_test = mnist_dataset_test[mnist_dataset_test['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, 1:785].values
    X_test = sc.fit_transform(X_test)
    Y_test = mnist_dataset_test[mnist_dataset_test['Label'].isin([label1,label2])].iloc[:, -1].values.ravel()
    return X_train,Y_train,X_test,Y_test
In [380]:
def calculateAccLinearSVM(X,y,test_X,test_Y):
    from sklearn.svm import LinearSVC
    clf = LinearSVC(random_state=10, tol=1e-5)
    clf = clf.fit(X,y)  
    Y_pred = clf.predict(test_X)
    return round(clf.score(X, y),4),round(metrics.accuracy_score(test_Y, Y_pred),4)
#X_train_img,Y_train_img,X_test_img,Y_test_img = defineSubsets(1,6)
In [381]:
def mergeClasses(dataset,pair,newLabel):
    print("inmerge")
    dataset.loc[dataset['Label'].isin([pair[0],pair[1]]),['Label']] = newLabel
    return dataset
In [382]:
import itertools
#print(my_list)
pairToBeCombined = []
accuracy =[]
accuracyTest =[]
totalPairs = 0 
newLabel = 11
newLabels = []
while (totalPairs != 1):
    minaAcc = 1 
    minaAccCorespTest = 1 
    minAccuracyPair = (-1,-1)
    listofVals = numpy.unique(mnist_dataset_train.Label)
    print(listofVals)
    combiPairs = itertools.combinations(listofVals, r=2)
    totalPairs = len(list(combiPairs))
    print("totalpairs" + str(totalPairs))
    print(list(combiPairs))
    for pair in itertools.combinations(listofVals, r=2):
        print(pair)
        X_train_img,Y_train_img,X_test_img,Y_test_img = defineSubsets(*pair)
        acc,accTest = calculateAccLinearSVM(X_train_img,Y_train_img,X_test_img,Y_test_img)
        print(pair)
        print(acc)
        if (acc < minaAcc):
            minaAcc = acc
            minaAccCorespTest = accTest
            minAccuracyPair = pair
    print(minaAcc)
    print(minAccuracyPair)
    newLabel = str(minAccuracyPair[0]) + '_'+ str(minAccuracyPair[1])
    mnist_dataset_train= mergeClasses(mnist_dataset_train,minAccuracyPair,newLabel)
    mnist_dataset_test= mergeClasses(mnist_dataset_test,minAccuracyPair,newLabel)
    print("new Label")
    #newLabel = newLabel + 1
    print(newLabel)
    pairToBeCombined.append(minAccuracyPair)
    accuracy.append(minaAcc)
    accuracyTest.append(minaAccCorespTest)
    newLabels.append(newLabel)
treeDF= pd.DataFrame({'pair': pairToBeCombined ,'newLabel' : newLabels,'acc' : accuracy ,'accTest' : accuracyTest})

from graphviz import Digraph # install this lib
dot = Digraph(comment='Mnist')

for i in range(0,10):
    dot.node(str(i), str(i))

for i in treeDF.sort_index(ascending=False).pair:
    #print(i)
    #print('\t' + str(i[0]) + ' [label='+ str(i[0]) + ']' in dot.body)
    #print('\t' + str(i[1]) + ' [label='+ str(i[1]) + ']' in dot.body)
    if (('\t' + str(i[0]) + ' [label='+ str(i[0]) + ']' in dot.body) != True):
        #print("makenode" + str(i[0]) )
        #dot.node(str(i[0]), str(i[0]))
        nodeX = str(i[0])
        accX = treeDF[treeDF['newLabel']==nodeX].acc.values
        accTestX = treeDF[treeDF['newLabel']==nodeX].accTest.values
        #print(nodeX)
        dot.node(nodeX,nodeX + "\nTrain Acc: " + str(accX) +  "\nTest Acc: " + str(accTestX))
    if (('\t' + str(i[1]) + ' [label='+ str(i[1]) + ']' in dot.body) != True):
        #print("make node")
        #print(i[1])
        #dot.node(str(i[1]), str(i[1]))
        nodeY = str(i[1])
        accY = treeDF[treeDF['newLabel']==nodeY].acc.values
        accTestY = treeDF[treeDF['newLabel']==nodeY].accTest.values
        dot.node(nodeY,nodeY + "\nTrain Acc: " + str(accY) +  "\nTest Acc: " + str(accTestY))
        #print(nodeY)
        #print("makenode" + str(i[1]) )
        

        
for (i,y,acc,accTest) in treeDF.sort_index(ascending=False).values:
    #print(i)
    dot.node(y,y + "\nTrain Acc: " + str(acc) +  "\nTest Acc: " + str(accTest))
    nodea = str(i[0]) +'_' + str(i[1])
    nodeb = str(i[0])
    nodec = str(i[1])
    dot.edge(nodea,nodeb)
    dot.edge(nodea,nodec)

from nltk import pos_tag
import re
In [387]:
wnl = SnowballStemmer("english")
stop_words = stopwords.words('english')

def cleanTextandStemming(text):
    #text = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text)
    text = re.sub('[^ a-zA-Z]',' ',text)
    text = re.sub(r' +', ' ', text)
    
    text=re.sub('\S*#(?:\[[^\]]+\]|\S+)+', ' ', text) #hastags
    text=re.sub('\S*@(?:\[[^\]]+\]|\S+)+', ' ', text) #mentions
    
    text=text.replace('\n',' ').replace('\r',' ') # line breaks and carriage returns
    
    text=text.replace(""," ") #Special characters
    text=text.replace(""," ")  #Special characters
  
    text = re.sub(r"(http(s?))?://\S+",' ',text) #links wiht http(s)
    text = re.sub(r"(www)?[\S]+\.[\S]+\.[\S]+",' ',text) #links with just xyz.xyz.com
    
    text=re.sub(r"[.,/*-/?\'\"\\;:\[\]{}!@$^()]+"," ",text,re.DOTALL|re.U|re.I) #puntuations
   
    text = re.sub(r"\s+", " ", text) #whitespaces
    text = stemWords(text)
    return(text)   

def stemWords(data):
    sentence=''
    for w in word_tokenize(data):
        word = '' 
        if ((w not in stop_words) and len(w)>2):
            word = wnl.stem(w)
            sentence = sentence + " " + word.lower()
    return sentence

In [390]:
def readFile(fileobj):
    while True:
        data = fileobj.read()
        if not data:
            break
        yield data
In [391]:
docList =[]
for fileobj in X_train:
    f = open(fileobj,'r',encoding="ISO-8859-1")
    for doc in readFile(f):
        #print("Before")
        #print(doc)
        cleanedText = cleanTextandStemming(doc)
        docList.append(cleanedText)

In [413]:
docsCountswithLabels = features1[wordDict.word.values].copy()
docsCountswithLabels['category'] = Y_train.values
lambdaVal = 30
distinctWords = docsCountswithLabels.shape[1]
categories = np.unique(Y_train.values)
#def calculateProbability(word,category):
#word = 'soc'
#classVal = 'talk.politics.mideast'
#count of word in all documents of class class val
finalWord = []
finalWordProb = []
finalWordClass = []


for catVal in categories:
    subset = docsCountswithLabels[docsCountswithLabels['category']==catVal]
    #print(subset.shape)
    M = 0
    if M==0:
        M = subset.loc[:, subset.columns != 'category'].sum().reset_index().iloc[:,1:2].rename(columns={0: "counts"}).sum().values
    for word in wordDict.word:
        cntWordClass = 0 
        deno = 0
        cntWordClass = subset[word].sum()           
        # This the the calculation as per formula below in summary
        prob = round((lambdaVal + cntWordClass)/ (distinctWords + lambdaVal + M[0]),4) 
        #print(prob)
        finalWord.append(word)
        finalWordClass.append(catVal)
        finalWordProb.append(prob)
summarWordsDF= pd.DataFrame({'word': finalWord ,'category': finalWordClass ,'probWordClass' : finalWordProb })
summarWordsDF.head()

def calculateYPredicted(dataset):
    Y_pred =[]
    categories = np.unique(Y_train.values)
    #print(categories)
    iter2= 0
    for doc in dataset.doc[0:10]:
        iter2 = iter2+1
        print(iter2)
        probVals =[]
        catVals =[]
        for classVal in categories:
            prob = 1.0000
            for w in word_tokenize(doc):
              
                if w in wordDict.word.values:
                    #print(w)
                    probClass = summarWordsDF[(summarWordsDF.word==w) & (summarWordsDF.category==classVal)]['probWordClass']
                    if (len(probClass) > 0):
                        if(probClass.values[0] > 0):     
                          
                            #print(probClass.values[0])
                            prob = prob * probClass.values[0]
                            #print(prob)
                        else:
                            prob = prob * 0.0001 #later needed : if wordDict condition not present very small val for missing words # cant set to zero ,this might be needed for missing words on vocab
                    else:       
                        prob = prob * 0.0001 #very small val for missing words # cant set to zero
            catVals.append(classVal)
            
            #print(prob)
            finalprob = prob*priorDF[priorDF.cat ==classVal]['priors'].values[0]
            
            probVals.append(finalprob) #multiply by prior
        b=np.argmax(probVals)
        #print(b)
        #print(catVals[b])
        Y_pred.append(catVals[b])
    return Y_pred

Summary Q6:¶

  • Here we are doing text classification using the naive bayes assumption
  • We build the model on entire corpus give of all 20 folders
  • We applied a smooting parameter Laplacian smooting(lambda in formula below) with a value of 30
  • There are 20 categories in the news corpus
  • We loaded the entire dataset and divided the entire newsfiles into train test of 75% and 25% resp
  • We further load each document and try to do some preprocessing as below:
    • We remove punctuations , carriage returns , newline characters, special characters , hashtags etc in the clean text method
    • We remove stop words using the nltk package
    • We remove all the words that are less than 2 chars
    • We also do stemming using the Snowball stemmer to bring the root form of the word
    • Finally we send the lowercase letters for further processing
  • The cleaned document is now further fed to count vectorizer that gives us the term frequecies
  • The use of count vectorizer is multifold here
    • It removes the left-over junk and breaks the document into tokens to further give its frequencies
    • I use the same to further sort filter and get the top 5000 words that are most frequent for further processing
    • Once this new dict is formed , I used the same vectorizer output in dataframe to further give me frequencies of these new 5000 words
  • Now summarWordsDF gets computed as per the formula
    • P(Wm|c) = (lambda + N(Wm|c))/(M + allmfrom1toM N(Wm|c) + lambda ))
  • We also compute priors of the 20 classes using the Y train dataset : priorDF
  • Further we now build a predictor method calculateYPredicted which takes the dataset provided , and computes the probabilities of all the words as per
    • Using cross to denote multiply below
    • first tokenizes all the words of each doc provided , then calculate the probabilities as below
    • P(c|doc) = P(Wm1|c) cross P(Wm2|c) cross P(Wm3|c)....P(WmM|c) * PriorProb(c)
    • P(WmM|c) : is coming from summarWordsDF filtered for that word for that class
    • Where PriorProb is the prior probability of the class and is coming from priorDF that we computed
  • Once we get the probabilities we check on which class did the max probability occur for the P(WmM|c) and we assign that class label for the dataset.
  • We compute the accuracy for both test and train datasets with the predicted output from the calculateYPredicted function by passing the document corpus which returns us the class labels predicted , which we compare with the actuals to get the accuracies on both the dataset
  • the cleansing and stemming steps are used and performed on the dataset before the documents are passed to the predictor
  • We ran the model on train and test data , the train accuracy is 0.3 and test accuracy is 0.6
  • We can run the model on more documents to get the overall train and test accuracies.
  • The model also handles probability of new words that are not in dict , however its toggle based and can be altered if needed
